    "title": "Ribollita",
    "subtitle": "The Tuscan bread and bean soup that thickens overnight",
    "excerpt": "Cannellini beans, cavolo nero, and country bread simmered into a thick Tuscan soup that is reheated the next day ,  which is when it is at its best. One of the most satisfying cold-weather soups in the Italian tradition.",
    "sourceNotes": "Ribollita (meaning 'reboiled') is a Tuscan peasant soup traditionally made by reheating leftover minestrone with stale bread. This version follows the standard modern approach with cannellini beans and cavolo nero.",
    "body": {
      "type": "doc",
      "content": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Ribollita means reboiled: it is made to be eaten the next day. The bread added at the end of the first cooking absorbs the broth overnight and transforms the soup into something thick, almost porridge-like, that only needs a hard reheat and a generous pour of olive oil to be ready. ",
              "type": "text"
            },
            {
              "text": "Cavolo nero",
              "type": "text",
              "marks": [
                {
                  "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                  "attrs": {
                    "termId": "cmprydph80000vkv4g8ikxoh5"
                  }
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "text": " is the traditional green; curly kale or Savoy cabbage work if cavolo nero is not available. Use stale bread ,  the older and drier the better, since it absorbs more broth.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
