        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Method",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Build the soffritto base",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Heat {{extra-virgin-olive-oil}} of olive oil in a large heavy pot over a medium-low heat. Add the {{onion}} onion, {{carrot}} carrots, and {{celery}} celery. Cook for 12 minutes until very soft. Add the {{garlic}} of garlic, {{thyme-dried}} of thyme, and {{rosemary}} of rosemary and cook for 2 minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Add tomatoes, beans, and stock",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add {{tinned-tomatoes}} of tinned tomatoes, crushing them with the back of a spoon. If using a Parmesan rind, add it now. Simmer for 10 minutes.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the {{cannellini-beans}} of drained cannellini beans and pour in {{stock-vegetable}} of hot stock. Bring to a simmer. Use the back of a spoon to roughly crush about a quarter of the beans against the side of the pot to thicken the broth.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Add the {{cavolo-nero}} of torn cavolo nero leaves. Simmer for 20 minutes until the greens are very tender.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 3
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Add the bread and rest",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "orderedList",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "Remove the Parmesan rind and rosemary sprig. Stir in {{bread}} of torn stale bread. Press the bread down into the soup so it absorbs the broth. Take off the heat and leave to rest for at least 1 hour, or refrigerate overnight.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "listItem",
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "content": [
                    {
                      "text": "To serve, reheat gently, stirring as the bread breaks down into the soup. Thin with a little water if it has become too thick. Taste and season with salt. Ladle into bowls and drizzle generously with olive oil. Finish with grated Parmesan if using.",
                      "type": "text"
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "troubleshooter",
          "attrs": {
            "items": [
              {
                "fix": "Add hot water or stock when reheating, stirring as it warms. Ribollita is meant to be thick but it should still move in the pot.",
                "cause": "The bread has absorbed a very large amount of broth overnight.",
                "symptom": "Soup is too thick to ladle"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Use stale bread, torn into small chunks rather than sliced. Press it down into the soup firmly. The lumpy stage is temporary; the second reheat smooths it out.",
                "cause": "The bread was added in large pieces or was too fresh and has become gluey rather than dissolving.",
                "symptom": "Bread has made the soup lumpy"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Give it the full 20 minutes of simmering. It should be dark, completely soft, and almost melting into the broth.",
                "cause": "Cavolo nero needs longer cooking than most cabbage varieties.",
                "symptom": "Cavolo nero is still tough"
              },
              {
                "fix": "Taste again on the second day before declaring it bland. A generous pour of good olive oil on each bowl at serving lifts the whole soup significantly.",
                "cause": "Ribollita improves overnight as the bread and beans continue to thicken the broth and the flavours meld.",
                "symptom": "Flavour is flat on the first day"
              }
            ]
          }
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "attrs": {
            "level": 2
          },
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Where this dish lives",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "content": [
            {
              "text": "Ribollita is Tuscan peasant food made from the most basic ingredients: beans, greens, stale bread, and olive oil. The name comes directly from the method ,  reboiled ,  because leftover minestrone was historically reheated the next day with bread added to make it more filling. Modern ribollita is made from scratch with this same intention: a soup designed not to be eaten fresh but to improve with a night's rest. It is a dish that rewards patience and a good bottle of olive oil.",
              "type": "text"
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    },
